default&#xa0;default1.default              defaultIntroductiondefault&#xa0;
default1.1
default              
defaultGreater 
defaultManchester
default warmly welcomes the CLG Select Committee Inquiry into fiscal devolution to cities and city regions. 
defaultThe inquiry is timely, following on from the 
defaultrecommendations of
default the Silk Commission
default and 
defaultLondon Finance Commission,
default and responding
default to the 
defaultlaunch of the City Centred Campaign for fiscal devolution 
defaultas 
defaultadvocated by 
defaultthe 
defaultCore Cities Group, 
defaultGreater London Authority
default and London Councils. 
default&#xa0;
default1.2
default              
defaultWe have argued 
defaultfor many years 
defaultthat democratically elected local leaders need to have control over the levers and resources which impact 
defaulton their ability to deliver economic growth and to improve the quality of life for local residents. It is essential that financial capa
defaultcity is aligned with functional economic areas so that growth and 
defaultpublic service 
defaultreform strategies 
defaultcan be
default integrated to support competitiveness and labour market productivity. 
defaultThe current system
default in this country
default, which is one of the most centralised in the 
defaultworld, limits local control over funding and means that cities are able to influence only around 5% of the taxes that are raised within them
default. This is 
defaultfar less than international competitors
default and
default constrain
defaults the ability of cities to deliver on growth and refo
defaultrm. 
defaultThe situation for major cities in 
defaultEngland
default is also out of step with moves to increase fiscal devolution to the devolved administrations. 
default&#xa0;
default1.3
default              
defaultWhilst there have been a number of steps towards further devolution, in particular through City Deals
default and the 
defaultforthcoming Growth Deals
default, we 
defaultview these as only the beginning of an ongoing process of decentralisation from Whitehall. The City Deals process has underlined the importance of differential devolution, whereby packages of powers and resources can be devolve
defaultd to local authorities based on the ability of those places to contribute to national priorities, as well as the capacity to demonstrate effective structures for local leadership, decision-making and accountability. One size does not fit all and devolution
default of powers and resources may be through different packages and to different timescales. 
default&#xa0;
default1.4
default              
defaultThe recently published Core Cities Growth Prospectus
default outlines the international evidence for decentralisation including fiscal devolution. The evidence shows tha
defaultt 
defaultcities with more local control over funding and policy achieve better economic results
default and are better placed to outperform the national economy
default. 
defaultThis work
default is supported by 
defaultProfessor Michael Parkinson’s
default 
defaultinternational 
defaultres
defaultearch
default,
default 
defaultwhich 
defaultillustrates
default that decentralising powers and resources 
defaultcoupled with
default spreading investment and encouraging high performance 
defaulti
defaultn a range of cities produce
defaults benefits on a national scale. 
