default2.1
default              
defaultGreater 
defaultManchester
default has
default established the 
defaultfirst statutory Combined Authority (GMCA) in the country, demonstrating the strength of local leadership and governance arrangements, and building on 25 years of joint working through the Association of Greater Manchester Authorities (AGMA). 
defaultA key 
defaultadvantage of the Combined Authority model is the joint governance arrangements which it provides for transport, economic development and regeneration, which allow for strategic prioritisation of the levers of growth across the functional economic area.
default 
defaultThe
default GMCA works closely with the Local Enterprise Partnership (LEP), 
defaultand together
default the GMCA and LEP provide a unique platform for governance and 
defaultaccountability across the city region
default for future devolution of powers and funding. 
default&#xa0;
default2.2
default              
defaultGreater 
defaultManchester’s econom
defaultic performance has been strong over recent decades, even during the recession – generating £48billion GVA per annum (around 4%
default of the national economy), and whilst
default the national picture remains uncertain, th
defaulte number of jobs in 
defaultGreater 
defaultManchester is
default predicte
defaultd to grow by more than 7% over the next decade. However, while the economy has grown, our skills base and productivity have not kept pace and we have not been able to reduce dependency or close the gap between the tax that is generated here and the cost of
default public services. 
defaultOur productivity gap is in part due to lower skills levels and lower levels of economic activity than the South East and if we are to fulfil our growth potential we must address that gap. 
default&#xa0;
default2.3
default              
defaultDespite the reductions in funding to publi
defaultc 
defaultservices, total public sector 
defaultspend in Greater Manchester increased from £21billion to £22billion between 2008/9 and 2011/12. Reductions in spend by local authorities, the police and fire services and others have been offset by increases in spending on wel
defaultfare and health and social care. The cost of providing p
defaultublic sector services is becoming
default increasingly unsustainable, with a greater proportion spent on the costs of dependency and less on opportuni
defaultties to increase growth and red
defaultuce the demand for those se
defaultrvices. 
default&#xa0;
default2.4
default              
defaultWe know from our analysis and experience that with the right tools we can create jobs and growth
default,
default but 
defaultthat 
defaultgrowth alone 
defaultwill not fundamentally change places or reduce the costs of dependency that fall to public services. We need to create 
defaultlevers to drive both growth and reform
default,
default which are
default 
defaultrooted in real 
defaultplaces with the capability and capacity to use them. 
defaultThis includes a
default local skills agenda
default, which
default will enable us to align the 
defaultskills of our residents with jobs both now and in the future, 
defaultthere
defaultby enabling
default more people to find sustainable work, productivity to rise and businesses to grow. 
defaultAn example of our innovative place based approach is the 
defaultGreater Manchester Work Programme Leavers scheme
default. This will provide integrated and intensive support to 
defaulthelp people 
defaultclaiming Employment Support Allowance who have not found sustained work through the Work Programme
default. 
default&#xa0;
default2.5
default              
defaultWe are 
defaulttherefore 
defaultseeking to create a platform for fiscal self-reliance tha
defaultt
default empowers local authorities to undertake their place shaping ro
defaultle to create high quality places that attract and retain more productive people and businesses. 
defaultOur approach to achieving this, based around the twin themes of growth and reform, is set out in the recently revised Greater 
defaultManchester Strategy ‘Stronger Toge
defaultther’
default and the Greater Manchester Growth and Reform Plan
default submitted to government as part of the Growth Deal Process. 
