defaultgrowth in places.
default The current system mitigates against innovation by treating local growth as a zero sum game – with growth in one locality being assumed to be at the expense of growth in another. 
default&#xa0;
default4.default              defaultFiscal measuresdefault&#xa0;
default4.1
default              
defaultFiscal devolution must play a significant role in 
defaultany realignment of the relationship between local authorities and central government. The current model rewards central government for behaviour and decisions made by local authorities, providing little incentive to communities.
default&#xa0;
default4.2
default              
defaultLocal authorities do r
defaultaise council tax locally, but the bandings are set nationally and central Government maintains significant control over the level of any council tax increases. Whilst the principle of council tax referendums provides direct accountability, the variable nat
defaulture of the referendum threshold set by central Government makes long term decision making for local authorities problematic.
default&#xa0;
default4.3
default              
defaultCouncil tax is only one property tax, and there is a strong case for others to be devolved to local authorities, such as stamp
default duty. Alongside retained business rates, local authorities would be incentivised to encourage economic activity such as house-buying in their area if they retained some or all of the stamp duty due on a property sale, and the funds could then be used to p
defaultrovide local services.
default&#xa0;
default4.4
default              
defaultThere is also a need for a wider debate on local taxation, and 
defaultin particular whether
default local authorities could be give
defaultn discretion to introduce other forms of taxation, for example a hotel room levy. Given the role local authoriti
defaultes play in promoting their areas and encouraging both tourism and inward investment, a hotel room levy would provide a source of funding for such services derived from their success.
default&#xa0;
default5.default              defaultPublic service reform default&#xa0;
default5.1
default              
defaultAs outlined above, i
defaultncentivising and rewa
defaultrding growth must be accompanied by more control over the other public sector resources which are spent in local areas. 
defaultGreater 
defaultManchester
default has been on a journey of reforming public services which has involved piloting integrated working in the most deprive
defaultd neighbourhoods of the city region, pioneering work on Troubled Families and the national whole place Community Budget Pilot. 
defaultOur Community Budget Pilot has addressed 
defaulthow to transform the way we deliver services in order to reduce dependency and demand, a
defaultnd to increase productivity through work and skills. Our final submission to government included a number of new delivery and investment models which cross traditional public sector boundaries and have the ability to achieve improved outcomes through earli
defaulter 
defaultintervention and prevention. 
defaultThis is part of a wider programme of Public Service Reform in Greater Manchester working on the reduction of demand and dependency – focusing on Early Years, Troubled Families, Transforming Justice, Health and Social Care an
defaultd Work and Low Skills. 
default&#xa0;
default5.2
default              
defaultA priority for us is to take the results of the 
defaultCommunity Budgets P
defaultilot forward as the basis of a potential new settlement between national and local government that supports, incentivises and responds to public sector reform. 
defaultA new way of capturing the benefits of growth must also not solely be related to business rates as a proxy of growth, but should also be related to new investment models which are designed to deliver savings by reducing dependency. This can only be deliver
defaulted on an individual place basis.
default&#xa0;
default6.default              defaultPlace based settlementsdefault&#xa0;
default6.1
default              
defaultGreater 
defaultManchester
default strongly supports the proposal within the 2013 Autumn Statement for government to work towards local public services having the same long term indicative budgets as depart
defaultments
default 
defaultand supporting local areas to deliver services differently if the
defaulty can show it will save money. 
defaultGreater certainty of future budgets would provide local partners with the impetus to invest now in public service reform that will deliver future savings.
default They will be able to decommission services no longer required in the knowledge that their investment will be recouped and recycled.  
default&#xa0;
default6.2
default              
defaultThis is strongly linked to the Greater Manchester Pub
defaultl
defaultic Service Reform approach, whereby we 
defaultare asking for the 
defaultfreedom to reinvest the return on capital projects, and on the increased tax income as businesses begin to do better as a result, we are also focused on the need to keep the savings made in places from reduced dependency for long enough for those changes t
defaulto people and places to become irreversible.
default              
default7.default              defaultJoint accountabilitydefault&#xa0;
default7.1
default              
defaultFiscal devolution is not just about whether powers should be devolved or remain at the centre. There are a range of policies and funding streams which need to reflect national and l
defaultocal priorities and where models of accountability could be explored in more detail. A solution may lie in creating a link between the channels of accountability already established by central government to manage its relationship with arms-length bodies, 
defaultand the arrangements for local accountability in place in local government.  
default&#xa0;
default8.default              defaultLocal government finance reformdefault&#xa0;
default8.1
default              
defaultAlthough the focus of the 
defaultinquiry relates to fiscal form it is also important to consider the wider 
defaultcontext for local government fi
defaultnance.
default 
defaultDespite some changes to the local government finance system, local authorities are still heavily reliant on central government funding to fund services. The part-localisation of business rates was an attempt to remedy this, but the outcome from the proces
defaults was deeply disappointing as the incentive effect was heavily diluted, and overall funding levels remain determined by central government.
default&#xa0;
default8.2
default              
defaultWhilst understanding and recognising the need for
default the
default Treasury to maintain control over public finances, there 
defaultalso needs to be recognition within the funding system of the strong financial stewardship of local government, accompanied with a more trusting relationship between central and local. 
defaultPrudential borrowing is a strong example of this, as it provides a fram
defaultework within which local authorities can borrow what they need for capital purposes, and which provides some reassurance to Treasury regarding the affordability of such borrowing.
default&#xa0;
default8.3
default              
defaultThe main sources of local funding are now both subject to direct 
defaultg
defaultovern
defaultment subsidy through the Council Tax Freeze Grants and the reduction in busin
defaultess rates following the Autumn S
defaulttatement. Experience from the past shows that once local taxation loses its local rationale, 
defaultthere is a 
defaultdanger that it loses credibility
default,
default and gover
defaultnment is faced with a fut
defaulture dilemma about whether to co
defaultntinue with its subsidy or find another solution.
default&#xa0;
default8.4
default              
defaultAny reform of the wider local government finance system
default 
defaultmust, at its core, retain the principle of equalisation, to ensure that there is an unde
defaultrlying fairness within the system. A key element of this must be a reassessment of council tax, and in particular the bandings used. House prices have grown at significantly different rates across the country since the bands were originally set, and this h
defaultas created an unequal system. Council tax bands must be 
defaultrevalued
default, in a similar way to business rates assessments, to ensure that the tax being charged on a property is fair wherever in the country it is.
